2. Related Work

We situate our contribution within the intersecting landscapes of geometric numerical integration and structure-preserving machine learning.

2.1 Geometric Numerical Integration

Variational integrators, introduced by Marsden and West (2001), discretize Hamilton's principle rather than the differential equations. The resulting DEL equations define a symplectic map with excellent long-term energy behavior. Key references include:

· Symplectic Integrators: Verlet, Ruth–Yoshida (1990), symplectic Runge–Kutta (Hairer, Lubich, Wanner 2006).
· Discrete Mechanics: Marsden & West (2001) provide the foundational theory; Lew et al. (2003) extend to constrained systems; Kharevych et al. (2006) apply to computer graphics.

Our framework directly inherits these properties by learning the discrete Lagrangian.

2.2 Hamiltonian and Lagrangian Neural Networks

· Hamiltonian Neural Networks (HNNs): Greydanus et al. (2019) propose learning a Hamiltonian function $\mathcal{H}_\theta(q, p)$ and using its symplectic gradient to evolve dynamics. While the learned vector field is Hamiltonian, external integration (e.g., Runge–Kutta) breaks symplecticity, causing energy drift.
· Lagrangian Neural Networks (LNNs): Cranmer et al. (2020) parameterize $L_\theta(q, \dot{q})$ and enforce Euler–Lagrange equations. Similar issues with external integrators persist.
· Symplectic ODE-Net / SympNets: Jin et al. (2020) and Chen et al. (2020) learn explicit symplectic maps via composition of shear transformations. These guarantee symplecticity but lack a Lagrangian/Hamiltonian interpretation.
· Hamiltonian Generative Networks: Toth et al. (2020) combine symplectic integration with generative modeling.

2.3 Discrete Variational Learning

· Variational Integrator Networks (VINs): Saemundsson et al. (2020) first proposed learning a discrete Lagrangian and enforcing DEL. Subsequent works (Bhatia et al. 2023, Lishkova et al. 2023) extended to controlled and dissipative systems.
· Forced Variational Integrator Networks (FVINs): Extend VINs to non-conservative systems via the discrete Lagrange–d'Alembert principle.
· Equivariant Variational Mechanics: Han et al. (2023) propose an equivariant graph network for learning discrete Lagrangians of particle systems.

Our work distinguishes itself by providing a comprehensive theoretical foundation with explicit discussion of assumptions and open problems.

2.4 Equivariant and Graph Neural Networks

· SE(3)-Transformers and Tensor Field Networks: Thomas et al. (2018), Fuchs et al. (2020) develop architectures that respect 3D roto-translational symmetries.
· Equivariant Graph Networks: Satorras et al. (2021), Finzi et al. (2021) provide general frameworks for building invariant/equivariant functions on graphs.
· Application to N-body: Cranmer et al. (2020) use graph networks for Hamiltonian learning; we adapt these ideas to discrete Lagrangians.

