6. SE(3)-Equivariant Architecture for N-Body Systems

We now construct a parameterization of $\mathcal{L}_\theta$ that respects the physical symmetries of the gravitational N-body problem.

6.1 Group-Theoretic Preliminaries

The configuration space is $Q = (\mathbb{R}^3)^N \cong \mathbb{R}^{3N}$. The system is invariant under:

· Translations: $T_{\mathbf{c}}: \mathbf{q}_i \mapsto \mathbf{q}_i + \mathbf{c}$ for $\mathbf{c} \in \mathbb{R}^3$.
· Rotations: $R: \mathbf{q}_i \mapsto R \mathbf{q}_i$ for $R \in \mathrm{SO}(3)$.
· Permutations: $\sigma: \mathbf{q}_i \mapsto \mathbf{q}_{\sigma(i)}$ for $\sigma \in S_N$ (if masses are identical).

Together, translations and rotations form the special Euclidean group $\mathrm{SE}(3) = \mathbb{R}^3 \rtimes \mathrm{SO}(3)$.

Definition 6.1 (Invariant Discrete Lagrangian). A function $\mathcal{L}_\theta: Q \times Q \to \mathbb{R}$ is SE(3)-invariant if for all $g = (\mathbf{c}, R) \in \mathrm{SE}(3)$,

\mathcal{L}_\theta(g \cdot q, g \cdot q') = \mathcal{L}_\theta(q, q'),

where $g \cdot q$ acts on each body as $g \cdot \mathbf{q}_i = R \mathbf{q}_i + \mathbf{c}$.

6.2 Invariant Feature Construction

To achieve invariance, we express $\mathcal{L}_\theta$ in terms of invariant scalars derived from the input pairs.

Pairwise Relative Quantities:
For two bodies $i$ and $j$, consider positions $\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{q}_j$ and the corresponding next-step positions $\mathbf{q}_i', \mathbf{q}_j'$. From these, we can form:

· Relative position vectors: $\mathbf{r}_{ij} = \mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j$, $\mathbf{r}_{ij}' = \mathbf{q}_i' - \mathbf{q}_j'$.
· Relative distances: $r_{ij} = \|\mathbf{r}_{ij}\|$, $r_{ij}' = \|\mathbf{r}_{ij}'\|$.
· Relative velocities (finite difference): $\mathbf{v}_{ij} \approx \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij}' - \mathbf{r}_{ij}}{h}$.
· Scalar invariants:
  · $r_{ij}$ and $r_{ij}'$ (already invariant under SE(3)).
  · $\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ij}'$ (dot product invariant under rotations).
  · $\|\mathbf{v}_{ij}\|$ (magnitude of relative velocity).
  · Masses $m_i, m_j$ (scalars).
  · Time step $h$ (scalar).

Additionally, to capture three-body and higher-order correlations, we include triplet invariants such as angles between relative position vectors: $\cos \theta_{ijk} = \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ik}}{r_{ij} r_{ik}}$, and similarly for $\mathbf{r}_{ij}'$. We incorporate these by extending edge features to include a summary of triplet geometry.

6.3 Neural Network Design

We propose a graph neural network (GNN) architecture that respects permutation invariance and SE(3) invariance.

Input Representation:
For a pair $(q, q')$, we construct a graph where each node $i$ has features $\mathbf{x}_i = [\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{q}_i', m_i] \in \mathbb{R}^{7}$. Edges $(i,j)$ are fully connected.

Edge Feature Computation:
For each directed edge $i \to j$, compute invariant scalars:

\mathbf{e}_{ij} = \left[ r_{ij}, r_{ij}', \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ij}'}{r_{ij} r_{ij}'}, \|\mathbf{v}_{ij}\|, m_i, m_j, h \right] \in \mathbb{R}^{7}.

(For $r_{ij}=0$, set the angular feature to 1.)

Triplet Feature Augmentation:
To capture three-body correlations, we compute for each pair $(i,j)$ the average of angle features with a third body $k$:

\alpha_{ij} = \frac{1}{N-2} \sum_{k \notin \{i,j\}} \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ik}}{r_{ij} r_{ik} + \epsilon}, \quad \alpha_{ij}' = \frac{1}{N-2} \sum_{k \notin \{i,j\}} \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij}' \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ik}'}{r_{ij}' r_{ik}' + \epsilon}.

These are appended to $\mathbf{e}_{ij}$, yielding a $9$-dimensional edge feature vector.

Edge Embedding:
Pass $\mathbf{e}_{ij}$ through an MLP $\phi_{\text{edge}}: \mathbb{R}^9 \to \mathbb{R}^d$ to obtain edge embeddings $\mathbf{h}_{ij}$.

Global Pooling:
To enforce permutation invariance, sum over all directed edges:

\mathbf{H} = \sum_{i \neq j} \mathbf{h}_{ij} \quad \in \mathbb{R}^d.

Scalar Readout:
Finally, map the global embedding to a scalar via an MLP $\psi_{\text{out}}: \mathbb{R}^d \to \mathbb{R}$:

\mathcal{L}_\theta(q, q') = \psi_{\text{out}}(\mathbf{H}).

Proposition 6.1 (Invariance). This architecture yields an $\mathcal{L}_\theta$ that is invariant under $\mathrm{SE}(3)$ and under permutations of identical bodies.

Proof. All edge features are SE(3)-invariant. Summation over edges ensures permutation invariance. ∎

Proposition 6.2 (Expressiveness and Separation).
The feature map is not fully injective; there exist distinct configurations that yield identical global sums. However, for generic configurations (distinct masses or non-degenerate geometries), the network can separate orbits up to continuous symmetries. Triplet augmentation increases capacity to capture three-body correlations.

Proof. Sum-pooling GNNs are bounded by the Weisfeiler-Lehman test (Xu et al., 2019). Triplet features add higher-order information. ∎

Extensions:

· Multi-scale GNN: For large $N$, hierarchical pooling or multiple message-passing rounds may improve expressiveness.
· Attention: Attention-weighted sums can emphasize close encounters.

6.4 Ensuring $C^2$ Smoothness

We use smooth activation functions (e.g., Softplus, GeLU) throughout. Edge features are smooth except at $r_{ij}=0$, which is avoided due to singular potential.

