9. Conclusion

We have presented Neural Variational Mechanics, a mathematically rigorous framework for learning the action functional of conservative dynamical systems. By parameterizing the discrete Lagrangian and enforcing the discrete Euler–Lagrange equations as a training objective, we obtain a neural integrator that is approximately symplectic and momentum-preserving by construction. We have provided comprehensive theoretical analysis, including symplecticity, generalization bounds, universal approximation, and error bounds under idealized assumptions. An SE(3)-equivariant graph neural network architecture ensures physical symmetries, and stabilization strategies address training challenges. We have explicitly identified the key assumptions and open problems—particularly the $C^2$-norm gap, Newton fragility, and scalability limits—that must be addressed in future empirical and theoretical work. This dissertation establishes a principled foundation for structure-preserving learning of chaotic dynamical systems, with applications to astrophysical N-body simulation and beyond.

