Appendix C: Group Theory and SE(3) Invariants

C.1 Special Euclidean Group SE(3)

The group $\mathrm{SE}(3) = \mathbb{R}^3 \rtimes \mathrm{SO}(3)$ consists of pairs $(\mathbf{c}, R)$ with $\mathbf{c} \in \mathbb{R}^3$, $R \in \mathrm{SO}(3)$. Group multiplication:
(\mathbf{c}_1, R_1) \cdot (\mathbf{c}_2, R_2) = (\mathbf{c}_1 + R_1 \mathbf{c}_2, R_1 R_2).


Action on $\mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^3$:
(\mathbf{c}, R) \cdot \mathbf{x} = R \mathbf{x} + \mathbf{c}.

Lie Algebra $\mathfrak{se}(3)$: Elements are $(\mathbf{v}, \boldsymbol{\omega}) \in \mathbb{R}^3 \times \mathbb{R}^3$ (with $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ representing a skew-symmetric matrix). The infinitesimal action on $\mathbf{x}$ is
\xi_Q(\mathbf{x}) = \boldsymbol{\omega} \times \mathbf{x} + \mathbf{v}.

C.2 Invariant Scalars from Pairwise Data

For two configurations $q = (\mathbf{q}_1, \dots, \mathbf{q}_N)$ and $q' = (\mathbf{q}_1', \dots, \mathbf{q}_N')$, consider pairwise relative vectors:
\mathbf{r}_{ij} = \mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j, \quad \mathbf{r}_{ij}' = \mathbf{q}_i' - \mathbf{q}_j'.


Under $(\mathbf{c}, R) \in \mathrm{SE}(3)$, both transform as $\mathbf{r}_{ij} \mapsto R \mathbf{r}_{ij}$ (translations cancel). Thus the following are invariant:

· Distances: $r_{ij} = \|\mathbf{r}_{ij}\|$, $r_{ij}' = \|\mathbf{r}_{ij}'\|$.
· Dot products: $\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ij}'$ (since $(R\mathbf{r}_{ij}) \cdot (R\mathbf{r}_{ij}') = \mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ij}'$).
· Relative speed magnitude: $\|\mathbf{v}_{ij}\| = \frac{1}{h} \|\mathbf{r}_{ij}' - \mathbf{r}_{ij}\|$.

These form a generating set of invariants for the action of $\mathrm{SE}(3)$ on pairs of points.

C.3 Triplet Invariants

To capture three-body correlations, we include angles between relative vectors:
\cos \theta_{ijk} = \frac{\mathbf{r}_{ij} \cdot \mathbf{r}_{ik}}{\|\mathbf{r}_{ij}\| \|\mathbf{r}_{ik}\|}.


This is invariant under rotations and translations. For the edge $(i,j)$, we can average over $k$ to get a triplet feature:
\alpha_{ij} = \frac{1}{N-2} \sum_{k \neq i,j} \cos \theta_{ijk}.

C.4 Proof of Invariance for GNN Architecture

Proposition C.1. The function $\mathcal{L}_\theta(q, q')$ defined by the GNN in Section 6.3 is $\mathrm{SE}(3)$-invariant.

Proof. The input to the network is a graph with node features $\mathbf{x}_i = [\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{q}_i', m_i]$. Under a transformation $g = (\mathbf{c}, R)$, each node feature transforms as $[\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{q}_i', m_i] \mapsto [R\mathbf{q}_i + \mathbf{c}, R\mathbf{q}_i' + \mathbf{c}, m_i]$.

Edge features $\mathbf{e}_{ij}$ are computed from relative quantities $\mathbf{r}_{ij}, \mathbf{r}_{ij}'$, which are invariant under translations, and the scalars (distances, dot products) are invariant under rotations. Masses are unchanged. Thus $\mathbf{e}_{ij}$ is invariant under $g$.

The edge embeddings $\mathbf{h}_{ij} = \phi_{\text{edge}}(\mathbf{e}_{ij})$ are invariant. The global sum $\mathbf{H} = \sum_{i \neq j} \mathbf{h}_{ij}$ is invariant. Finally, $\psi_{\text{out}}(\mathbf{H})$ is invariant. ∎

