Appendix E: Additional Lemmas and Technical Background

E.1 Discrete Grönwall Lemma

Lemma E.1 (Discrete Grönwall Inequality). Let $\{x_k\}_{k=0}^\infty$ be a sequence of non-negative numbers satisfying
x_{k+1} \le (1 + a) x_k + b, \quad a \ge 0, \ b \ge 0.


Then for all $k \ge 0$,
x_k \le (1+a)^k x_0 + \frac{(1+a)^k - 1}{a} b.

Proof. Unfold the recurrence:
x_1 \le (1+a) x_0 + b,


x_2 \le (1+a)^2 x_0 + (1+a)b + b,


and by induction,
x_k \le (1+a)^k x_0 + b \sum_{j=0}^{k-1} (1+a)^j = (1+a)^k x_0 + b \frac{(1+a)^k - 1}{a}.


∎

For the vector case with $\|e_{k+1}\| \le (1+a) \|e_k\| + b$, the same bound holds for the norm.

E.2 Inverse Function Theorem and DEL Map

Proposition E.2 (Existence of DEL Map). If $D_1 D_2 L_{d,h}(q_k, q_{k+1})$ is invertible at a point, then the DEL equation $D_2 L_{d,h}(q_{k-1}, q_k) + D_1 L_{d,h}(q_k, q_{k+1}) = 0$ defines $q_{k+1}$ locally as a smooth function of $(q_{k-1}, q_k)$.

Proof. Fix $(q_{k-1}, q_k)$. The equation is $F(q_{k+1}) = D_2 L_{d,h}(q_{k-1}, q_k) + D_1 L_{d,h}(q_k, q_{k+1}) = 0$. The Jacobian $\frac{\partial F}{\partial q_{k+1}} = D_1 D_2 L_{d,h}(q_k, q_{k+1})$. If this is invertible, the Implicit Function Theorem guarantees a unique local solution $q_{k+1} = \Psi(q_{k-1}, q_k)$. ∎

Corollary E.3. Non-degeneracy condition: $\det D_1 D_2 L_{d,h} \neq 0$ ensures the integrator is well-defined.

E.3 Backward Error Analysis for Symplectic Integrators

Theorem E.4 (Modified Equation). For a symplectic integrator of order $p$ applied to a Hamiltonian system, there exists a modified Hamiltonian $\tilde{\mathcal{H}} = \mathcal{H} + h^p \mathcal{H}_p + h^{p+1} \mathcal{H}_{p+1} + \cdots$ such that the numerical trajectory is exponentially close to the exact flow of $\tilde{\mathcal{H}}$ over times $T = \mathcal{O}(e^{c/h})$.

Proof. See Hairer, Lubich, & Wanner (2006), Chapter IX. The proof constructs a formal series for the modified Hamiltonian and uses the symplecticity to bound the remainder. ∎

This result underlies the long-time near-conservation of energy for variational integrators and justifies the expectation that our neural integrator, if sufficiently close to a symplectic reference, will exhibit bounded energy error over long horizons.

E.4 Covering Numbers and Rademacher Complexity

Definition E.1 (Covering Number). The covering number $\mathcal{N}(\epsilon, \mathcal{F}, \|\cdot\|)$ is the minimum number of balls of radius $\epsilon$ needed to cover the function class $\mathcal{F}$.

Lemma E.5 (Dudley's Entropy Integral Bound). The Rademacher complexity $\mathcal{R}_n(\mathcal{F})$ satisfies
\mathcal{R}_n(\mathcal{F}) \le \inf_{\alpha > 0} \left( 4\alpha + 12 \int_{\alpha}^{\infty} \sqrt{\frac{\log \mathcal{N}(\epsilon, \mathcal{F}, L_2)}{n}} \, d\epsilon \right).

For neural networks with bounded weights, the covering number grows polynomially in $1/\epsilon$, yielding $\mathcal{R}_n(\mathcal{F}) = \mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{n})$.

E.5 Weisfeiler-Lehman Graph Isomorphism Test

Theorem E.6 (Xu et al., 2019). Message-passing GNNs with sum/mean aggregation are at most as powerful as the Weisfeiler-Lehman (WL) graph isomorphism test in distinguishing non-isomorphic graphs.

Our architecture uses sum-pooling of edge features without iterative message passing. This corresponds to a 1-WL test on the line graph. While not fully expressive for all graphs, for N-body systems with distinct masses or asymmetric configurations, the continuous nature of the features (distances, angles) provides sufficient separation in practice.

